In [44]:
# to check stationarity of the data
roll_mean = df['Foot_fall'].rolling(window=12).mean()
roll_std = df['Foot_fall'].rolling(window=12).std()


orig = plt.plot(df['Foot_fall'],color = 'blue',label='Original')
mean = plt.plot(roll_mean, color = 'red',label = 'Rolling Mean')
std = plt.plot(roll_std,color='black',label='Rolling Std')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.title('Rolling Mean and Standard Deviation')
plt.show(block=False)
In [45]:
# Dickey Fuller Test
print("P-value:",np.round(adfuller(df['Foot_fall'].dropna())[1],decimals=2))

P-value: 0.85

Estimation¶

In [70]:
df.index.freq = "MS"
model = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(df['Foot_fall'],order=(1,1,1),seasonal_order=(1,1,0,12))
results = model.fit()
print(results.summary())

mse = ((df_forecasted - df_truth) ** 2).mean()
print('The Mean Squared Error of our forecasts is {}'.format(round(mse, 2)))
